{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17563693","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17563693"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T23:03:42+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T23:03:42+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16850"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16850","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16850"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.24,0.42,0.09,0.04,0.21]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9540"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"89979"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9540","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9540"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16850"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74138"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"27"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1787"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4976"},{"type":"tags","id":"4982"},{"type":"tags","id":"8118"},{"type":"tags","id":"8986"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11635"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22537"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30653"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43664"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"89979","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/89979"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 62-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with progressive shortness of breath over the past two years. He worked as an underground coal miner for 25 years until retiring five years ago, primarily in tunnel construction and rock cutting. He has a 30 pack-year smoking history but quit smoking eight years ago. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well. His pulse rate is 82/min, blood pressure 135/85 mmHg, respiratory rate 20/min, SpO2 94% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. There are bilateral fine crackles on chest auscultation. Spirometry shows a mixed restrictive-obstructive pattern with FEV1/FVC ratio of 0.65 and reduced total lung capacity. A chest X-ray shows bilateral small rounded opacities predominantly in the upper zones with background reticular changes, evidence of hilar node calcification, and some irregular linear opacities in the mid-zones.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Simple coal workers\u0027 pneumoconiosis","Mixed dust pneumoconiosis","Progressive massive fibrosis","Caplan syndrome","Silicosis"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with features suggesting mixed dust pneumoconiosis, given his history of tunnel construction and rock cutting in coal mining which typically involves exposure to both coal dust and crystalline silica. The presence of hilar node calcification and irregular linear opacities is particularly suggestive of silica exposure, while the upper zone small rounded opacities are consistent with coal dust exposure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMixed dust pneumoconiosis\u003C/strong\u003E occurs when workers are exposed to multiple types of inorganic dust. In coal mining, particularly tunnel construction and rock cutting, workers are often exposed to both coal dust and crystalline silica. The combination of rounded opacities (typical of coal dust) and irregular linear opacities with hilar node calcification (typical of silica) is characteristic of mixed dust pneumoconiosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESimple coal workers\u0027 pneumoconiosis\u003C/strong\u003E typically shows only small rounded opacities without the hilar node calcification or irregular linear opacities that suggest silica exposure. The mixed pattern on spirometry and the occupational history of tunnel construction make simple CWP less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProgressive massive fibrosis\u003C/strong\u003E would show large opacities \u0026gt;1cm in diameter, which are not described in this case. While this patient may progress to PMF, the current radiological findings do not support this diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECaplan syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E is a rare but distinct condition characterized by the rapid development of multiple well-defined rounded nodules in coal workers who have rheumatoid arthritis. These nodules typically develop within weeks to months, unlike the gradual progression seen in standard pneumoconiosis. The nodules are often peripheral and can cavitate. This patient has no features of rheumatoid arthritis such as joint pain or morning stiffness, making this diagnosis unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESilicosis\u003C/strong\u003E alone typically shows more prominent hilar node calcification and eggshell calcification, with a predominance of irregular linear opacities rather than the mixed pattern seen here. While silica exposure is clearly present, the combination of findings suggests mixed dust exposure rather than pure silicosis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Coal workers\u0027 pneumoconiosis (CWP) develops after prolonged exposure to coal dust, typically requiring 10+ years of underground mining.","Mixed dust pneumoconiosis commonly occurs in tunnel construction workers due to combined exposure to coal dust and crystalline silica.","Hilar lymph node calcification is a characteristic finding of silica exposure in pneumoconiosis.","Respiratory protection and dust control measures are essential for prevention of occupational lung diseases.","Caplan syndrome is characterized by rapidly developing nodules in coal workers with rheumatoid arthritis."],"references":["Centers for Disease Control and Prevention. Occupational exposure to respirable coal mine dust. CDC 1995 Available at: https://www.cdc.gov/niosh/docket/archive/pdfs/niosh-242/0242-090195-criteriadocument.pdf","Blackley DJ, Halldin CN, Laney AS. Continued Increase in Prevalence of Coal Workers\u0027 Pneumoconiosis in the United States, 1970\u20132017. Am J Public Health. 2018;108(9):1220-1222.","Chong S, Lee KS, Chung MP, Han J, Kwon OJ, Kim TS. Pneumoconiosis: Comparison of imaging and pathologic findings. Radiographics. 2006;26(1):59-77 Available at: https://doi.org/10.1148/rg.261055068"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74138"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16850"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74138","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/74138"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-11T15:00:39+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-11T15:00:53+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9540"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"89979"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory Medicine","synonyms":["Pulmonology"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"p